T1  - Large business customer response to time-of-day electricity rates
AU  - Park, Rolla Edward
AU  - Acton, Jan Paul
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 26
IS  - 1
SP  - 229
EP  - 252
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/09/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(84)90019-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407684900198
AB  - This study reports an initial analysis of changes in relative peak electricity consumption for almost 4,000 industrial and commercial customers in ten U.S. utilities with time-of-day (TOD) rates now in effect. Relative peak loads declined about one percentage point on average when TOD rates were introduced. A small fraction of customers reduced their peak loads a lot, but most customers (including commercial customers as a whole) have apparently not as yet changed their consumption patterns in response to TOD rates. Average change in load differs significantly by utility, industry, and year, and those changes are statistically related to the terms of the time-of-day rates customers faced. Changes in load, while small in percentage terms, are large enough to justify TOD rates on a benefit/cost evaluation. Welfare gains average over $1000 per year per customer, against a metering cost of approximately $65 per year when new meters are needed to monitor TOD rates.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Estimation of time-of-use pricing response in the absence of experimental data: An application of the methodology of data transferability
AU  - Aigner, Dennis J.
AU  - Leamer, Edward E.
