DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(84)90017-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407684900174
AB  - Using data from five experimental implementations of residential TOU rates in the United States, we estimate a consumer demand model for each experiment, and test the hypothesis that the elasticities of substitution are identical across experiments. The model is derived from an indirect utility function that permits the modelling to be separated into three stages. At each stage the parameters depend upon appliance stocks, housing characteristics, and climate. We do not reject the hypothesis that the parameters determining the elasticities of substitution are identical across experiments. This yields a generally applicable model for predicting residential response to TOU rates.
